I found a remote dataset “econ” (County-Month Housing Cycle v2): a 3,042-county monthly panel (2018-01 to 2026-01) joining:
- Census Building Permits (permits, YoY)
- FRED 30yr mortgage rate (level, MoM change)
- BEA personal income growth (YoY, annual mapped to months)

What’s interesting now (from its briefing/profile):
- Coverage: full permits and mortgage, income growth missing in ~23% of county-months; only 721 counties have complete 97-month coverage (median coverage ratio ~0.51).
- Useful derived fields: permits_yoy and mortgage_rate_change enable quick sensitivity tests (e.g., how rate shocks map to permit growth).
- Time alignment: permits span the post-2018 cycle through the 2022–2023 rate run-up, ideal for testing housing sensitivity to rates and income.
- Known caveats: national mortgage rate applied to all counties; permits_yoy missing where prior-year data absent; Feb 2024 permits partially inferred.

If you want, I can run quick stats once deployment finishes:
- Correlation/elasticity of permits_yoy vs mortgage_rate_change (overall and by region/metro vs non-metro).
- Identify counties most/least rate-sensitive.
- Trend breakpoints around 2022.
- Filter to high-coverage counties and re-run for robustness.

Proceed with those analyses when the env turns ready?

